<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="234" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1615,2037]" pageId="8" pageNumber="234">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1868,1893]" pageId="8" pageNumber="234">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Head, patagia, tegulae and dorsal surface of thorax and abdomen, white. Forewing white with the veins brown. Hindwing white. Valvae slightly longer than the uncus. Saccus as a large triangle. Phallus elongated, slightly sinusoidal and somewhat sclerotized. Vesica membranous with presence of one row of strongly sclerotized cornuti.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="235" pageId="8" pageNumber="234" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1615,2037]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,824]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="235" pageId="8" pageNumber="234">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,2012,2037]" pageId="8" pageNumber="234">Description. Male. Head.</emphasis>
Proboscis light brown. Palpi predominantly white, not exceeding vertex in length. Frons white, longer than wide. Vertex, occiput and scape white. Ocular ring brown with a bluish hue. Antennae white with brown scales at the base of each flagellomere. Medial rami length approximately three times the width of the shaft. Rami decreasing in length gradually towards the tip of the antennae, being absent distally. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1340,1436,223,248]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Thorax.</emphasis>
Dorsal surface of meso- and metathorax, including patagia and tegulae, white. Foreleg coxae white. Foreleg femora, tibia and tarsi white and the inner surface brown. Epiphysis light brown. Midleg coxae and femora white, tibia and tarsi white and the posterior surface brown. Hindlegs white. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[933,1064,332,357]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Forewings.</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[1263,1383,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" unit="mm" value="11.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="11.0">11‒12 mm</quantity>
(n = 5). Dorsally white with light brown veins and a brown costal margin. Ventrally white, with grey scales in the anterior area of the discal cell, on radial veins and in the distal half of median and cubital veins. The brown veins are more contrasting in the distal half, toward the termen. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[797,934,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Hindwings.</emphasis>
Dorsal and ventral surfaces almost identical, predominantly covered with white scales. On the ventral side, grey scales present between the costal margin and the radial veins. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[345,469,511,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Countertympana on dorsal and ventral side white. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1066,1176,511,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1195,1336,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 43‒46" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1357,1379]" captionTargetBox="[348,1245,894,1328]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[340,1248,877,1336]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 43‒46. Gloora canae sp. nov., male genitalia; dorsal (43), ventral (44), lateral (45), phallus (46). Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452147/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Figs. 43‒46</figureCitation>
). Saccus developed. Tegumen as wide as the vinculum, glabrous. Anterior margin of tegumen with a deep U-shaped invagination, slightly sclerotized. Posterior margin of tegumen straight, membranous in the middle, from which two structures in the form of sclerotized tongues emerge. Uncus unilobed, glabrous, wide at base, acute toward the distal end. Juxta extended, sclerotized, wide at base. Valvae symmetrical, slightly longer than the uncus; in lateral view thin and slightly curved. Toward the distal end, dorsal and ventral processes present. Ventral process membranous and covered with setae. Dorsal process slender, sclerotized and acute. Phallus cylindrical, slightly sinusoidal and somewhat sclerotized. Vesica membranous with a row of strongly sclerotized cornuti. Coremata with additional scale bunches (
<figureCitation box="[497,578,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURES 47‒50" captionStartId="10.[151,264,536,558]" captionTargetBox="[151,1403,193,515]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,515]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 47‒50. Dense clusters of scales, representing crystal scales (cs)(sensu Boppré et al. 2018) at the base of coremata (co) as seen in a freshly killed specimen in which coremata were artificially protruded (47) and in a KOH abdominal preparation of Gloora alba comb. nov. Same structures in KOH preparations of G. sericea comb. nov. (49) and G. canae sp. nov. (50)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452149/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) at the base of coremata tubes (as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Druce" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[993,1042,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Eucereon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[993,1042,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Boppré" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Zerny" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[1097,1178,800,823]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Gloora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis box="[1097,1178,800,823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">sericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, above).
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1427,1357,1379]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452147/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" startId="9.[151,264,1357,1379]" targetBox="[348,1245,894,1328]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1427,1357,1379]" box="[151,1427,1357,1379]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,340,1357,1379]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">FIGURES 43‒46.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Boppré, 2018" authorityName="Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Boppré" authorityYear="2018" box="[346,485,1357,1379]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Gloora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[346,485,1357,1379]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Gloora canae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[492,572,1357,1379]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,572,1357,1379]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male genitalia; dorsal (43), ventral (44), lateral (45), phallus (46). Scale bar: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1460,1953]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1460,1485]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Female.</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[495,575,1461,1485]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="9" pageNumber="235" unit="mm" value="13.0">13 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). Similar to males, but medial rami as long as the shaft width. In the forewings the costal margin is white. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[586,696,1496,1521]" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[714,801,1496,1521]" captionStart="FIGURE 51‒54" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1295,1317]" captionTargetBox="[155,1423,720,1264]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,700,1273]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 51‒54. Gloora alba comb. nov. (51), G. mundula comb. nov. (52), G. sericea comb. nov. (53), G. canae sp. nov. (54), female genitalia (bursae). Scale bars: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452151/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="235">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
). Ninth tergite slightly sclerotized. Papillae anales with relatively long setae. Anterior and posterior apophyses of the same size. Ostium and antrum centralized. Antevaginal lamella membranous and postvaginal lamella sclerotized. Ductus bursae wide, flattened, sinusoidal and membranous, except for the distal third of the dorsal side, which is sclerotized. Corpus bursae oval and membranous with small spicules on more than half its surface. Ductus seminalis emerging at the end of the ventral side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
